{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636602","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636602"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:30:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:30:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17594"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17594","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17594"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10308"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115233"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10308","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10308"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17594"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97241"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5392"},{"type":"tags","id":"5395"},{"type":"tags","id":"7794"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24102"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24107"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115233","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115233"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher wants to investigate the relationship between smoking status and lung function in adults aged 40-60 years. They collect data on smoking history and perform spirometry tests on 500 participants during a single clinic visit.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a key limitation of this cross-sectional study design?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cannot determine temporal sequence between exposure and outcome","Requires too large a sample size","Takes too long to complete","Costs more than other study designs","Produces results that cannot be generalised"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe main limitation of this cross-sectional study design is that it \u003Cstrong\u003Ecannot determine temporal sequence between exposure and outcome\u003C/strong\u003E. Since data on smoking and lung function are collected simultaneously, we cannot establish whether poor lung function preceded or followed smoking behaviour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequires too large a sample size\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as cross-sectional studies often require smaller sample sizes than cohort studies. \u003Cstrong\u003ETakes too long to complete\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because cross-sectional studies are typically quick to complete as data is collected at one time point. \u003Cstrong\u003EProduces results that cannot be generalised\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect since with appropriate sampling methods, results can be generalised to the target population. \u003Cstrong\u003ECosts more than other study designs\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as cross-sectional studies are generally less expensive than longitudinal studies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECross-sectional studies are useful for determining disease prevalence and generating hypotheses, but their inability to establish causation is a key limitation. This makes them less suitable for investigating cause-and-effect relationships.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cross-sectional studies examine exposures and outcomes at a single point in time.","Cross-sectional studies can determine prevalence but not incidence of disease.","Cross-sectional studies cannot establish temporal relationships between variables."],"references":["Weaver A, Goldberg S. Clinical Biostatistics and Epidemiology Made Ridiculously Simple. MedMaster, Miami. 2012. Chapter 5; pg 24.","Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97241"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17594"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97241"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T10:22:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T10:22:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10308"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115233"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4948"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":[],"descripti